WEBVTT

00:05.000 --> 00:12.000
Now that we know how the point of purchase and expenditure is determined,

00:12.000 --> 00:15.000
we can plan the assortment of products,

00:15.000 --> 00:22.000
we can move on to planning the production of several types of products,

00:22.000 --> 00:26.000
and we can also introduce a new concept.

00:26.000 --> 00:30.000
This concept is called the marginal profit.

00:30.000 --> 00:35.000
So, the use of the marginal profit to determine the point of purchase and expenditure.

00:35.000 --> 00:38.000
What is a marginal profit?

00:38.000 --> 00:43.000
It is denoted by the letter CM.

00:43.000 --> 00:46.000
What does CM mean? Contribution Margin.

00:46.000 --> 00:57.000
So, the marginal profit is the amount left after subtracting all variable costs from the sales volume.

00:57.000 --> 01:02.000
S is sales.

01:02.000 --> 01:06.000
VC is variable costs.

01:06.000 --> 01:10.000
CM is contribution margin.

01:10.000 --> 01:14.000
This is the marginal profit.

01:16.000 --> 01:26.000
The marginal profit of the product line is the net contribution of the coverage of the constant costs and the profit.

01:26.000 --> 01:35.000
Accordingly, the profit is what remains after the payment of the constant costs and subtraction from the marginal profit.

01:35.000 --> 01:40.000
There are different concepts of the profit.

01:40.000 --> 01:45.000
Let's look at this idea in more detail.

01:45.000 --> 01:51.000
What does the net contribution of the coverage of the constant costs and the profit mean?

01:51.000 --> 01:59.000
According to this idea, we consider the constant costs,

01:59.000 --> 02:06.000
what we called F and C, as an investment.

02:06.000 --> 02:15.000
We invest the constant costs in the beginning of the business, in the beginning of the production.

02:15.000 --> 02:26.000
After that, we expect that the investments will be paid off.

02:26.000 --> 02:28.000
How can they be paid off?

02:28.000 --> 02:33.000
They can be paid off by the production and sales of the product.

02:33.000 --> 02:42.000
But each unit of the product requires us to spend additional costs on each unit,

02:42.000 --> 02:47.000
which we will call variable costs or VC.

02:47.000 --> 02:55.000
Moreover, we will sell each unit at a certain price.

02:55.000 --> 03:02.000
Thus, the difference between the price of the sale and the variable costs

03:02.000 --> 03:09.000
will be the small amount, which is called the marginal profit.

03:09.000 --> 03:13.000
The word marginal means the limit.

03:13.000 --> 03:24.000
We take one unit, and one unit gives us a certain contribution to the coverage of the constant costs.

03:24.000 --> 03:33.000
The more we produce, the more we see the coverage of the constant costs.

03:33.000 --> 03:37.000
We covered the constant costs.

03:37.000 --> 03:40.000
What's left?

03:40.000 --> 03:48.000
Everything we get after covering the constant costs is our profit.

03:48.000 --> 03:54.000
We see that the profit we get is different from the marginal profit.

03:54.000 --> 03:59.000
The marginal profit is one single unit,

03:59.000 --> 04:05.000
which is the profit from the variable costs we get.

04:05.000 --> 04:13.000
But this profit is obtained before we include the analysis of the constant costs.

04:13.000 --> 04:20.000
The profit is what is left after paying the constant costs,

04:20.000 --> 04:24.000
covering, crossing the point of payback,

04:24.000 --> 04:27.000
and subtracting from the marginal profit,

04:27.000 --> 04:34.000
which is made by the production and sales of each new unit of the product.

04:35.000 --> 04:45.000
The profit is obtained by the marginal profit,

04:45.000 --> 04:52.000
the total marginal profit, if we count it for the entire produced product,

04:52.000 --> 04:59.000
and from this total marginal profit we subtract the fixed costs,

04:59.000 --> 05:02.000
that is, the constant costs.

05:02.000 --> 05:15.000
The point of profitability can be expressed as the point where the marginal profit minus the total constant costs is zero.

05:15.000 --> 05:21.000
Or the marginal profit equals the constant costs.

05:21.000 --> 05:31.000
The point of profitability in the international definition is denoted by the Latin letters B and I,

05:31.000 --> 05:37.000
which means in English it sounds like a break-even point.

05:37.000 --> 05:49.000
That is, the marginal profit per unit, multiplied by the point of profitability in units,

05:49.000 --> 05:54.000
that is, the so-called break-even contribution margin,

05:54.000 --> 05:57.000
multiplied by the break-even,

05:57.000 --> 06:03.000
all this minus the constant costs is zero.

06:05.000 --> 06:10.000
From here we can find out what the point of profitability is.

06:10.000 --> 06:18.000
So, these will be the constant costs divided by the marginal profit per unit.

06:19.000 --> 06:25.000
So, we recall the concept we presented a few minutes ago.

06:25.000 --> 06:32.000
We first make investments, we consider the opening of a new business,

06:32.000 --> 06:35.000
the production of new products as an investment,

06:35.000 --> 06:38.000
that is, these are constant costs.

06:38.000 --> 06:44.000
But the production of each new unit of the product requires variable costs

06:44.000 --> 06:49.000
and also requires the establishment of a certain sales price.

06:49.000 --> 06:54.000
The sales price minus the variable costs and there is a marginal profit,

06:54.000 --> 06:58.000
that is, the marginal profit from the production of each new unit.

06:58.000 --> 07:01.000
The marginal profit per unit.

07:01.000 --> 07:10.000
And the point of profitability per unit equals the constant costs

07:10.000 --> 07:14.000
divided by the marginal profit per unit.

07:14.000 --> 07:27.000
Now we will look at an example where we consider a different number of units produced and sold.

07:27.000 --> 07:31.000
We operate with the same symbols that we studied.

07:31.000 --> 07:33.000
We will repeat them again.

07:33.000 --> 07:38.000
S is sales, this is income from sales.

07:38.000 --> 07:41.000
In this case, it is 900 rubles per unit.

07:41.000 --> 07:47.000
If we recall, we produce cast-iron stands.

07:47.000 --> 07:51.000
Vc is the variable costs.

07:51.000 --> 07:57.000
They are subtracted and the variable costs are equal to 500 rubles per unit.

07:57.000 --> 08:01.000
Cm is the marginal profit.

08:01.000 --> 08:05.000
It is equal to 400 rubles per unit.

08:05.000 --> 08:15.000
Cm is the result of subtraction of the variable costs from the income from sales.

08:15.000 --> 08:22.000
Next, we subtract the constant costs, that is, Fc.

08:22.000 --> 08:28.000
And after that, we can get the amount of profit or loss.

08:29.000 --> 08:34.000
The profit is denoted by the letter P, which means profit.

08:34.000 --> 08:40.000
Next, we consider three different options.

08:40.000 --> 08:48.000
In one option, we have 250 units produced and sold.

08:48.000 --> 08:51.000
In the other option, we have 500 units.

08:51.000 --> 08:54.000
In the third option, we have 750 units.

08:54.000 --> 09:00.000
If we recall, 500 is equal to the value of the point of purchase.

09:00.000 --> 09:07.000
That is, the income from sales will be 900 times 500.

09:07.000 --> 09:15.000
900 times 250 equals 225,000.

09:15.000 --> 09:22.000
Minus the variable costs, 500 rubles per unit.

09:23.000 --> 09:27.000
And at the same time, we have 250 units.

09:27.000 --> 09:34.000
500 times 250 equals 125,000 rubles.

09:34.000 --> 09:43.000
The marginal profit will be equal to 225,000 rubles minus 125,000 rubles.

09:43.000 --> 09:51.000
This is equal to 100,000 rubles, that is, 400 rubles per unit.

09:51.000 --> 09:55.000
Next, we subtract the constant costs,

09:55.000 --> 10:03.000
which will not depend on how many units we produced and sold.

10:03.000 --> 10:09.000
And we see that when we produce 250 units,

10:09.000 --> 10:17.000
we get 100,000 minus 200,000 equals minus 100,000.

10:17.000 --> 10:23.000
100,000 in brackets means that this value is negative.

10:23.000 --> 10:25.000
This is a loss.

10:25.000 --> 10:28.000
We are still bearing a loss.

10:28.000 --> 10:34.000
Next, we increase the number of units produced and sold.

10:34.000 --> 10:36.000
Now we have 500 units.

10:36.000 --> 10:41.000
If we remember, this was the point of purchase.

10:41.000 --> 10:44.000
Again, we repeat the calculation.

10:44.000 --> 10:50.000
900 times 500 equals 450,000.

10:50.000 --> 10:56.000
The variable costs, 500 times 500 equals 250,000.

10:56.000 --> 11:05.000
The marginal profit is equal to 450,000 minus 250,000 equals 200,000.

11:05.000 --> 11:10.000
Minus the constant costs, which do not depend on the number of units produced.

11:10.000 --> 11:13.000
So, what do we get?

11:13.000 --> 11:15.000
We get zero.

11:15.000 --> 11:21.000
Zero means that the costs are covered, but the profit is not received.

11:21.000 --> 11:24.000
That is, everything we have produced,

11:24.000 --> 11:27.000
we have covered the costs,

11:27.000 --> 11:30.000
covered the initial investments

11:30.000 --> 11:34.000
that we made in order to start our business.

11:34.000 --> 11:36.000
We go further.

11:36.000 --> 11:41.000
Now we have 750 units produced and sold.

11:41.000 --> 11:45.000
The income from the sale is equal to 900 rubles per unit,

11:45.000 --> 11:52.000
multiplied by 750 units equals 675,000 rubles.

11:52.000 --> 11:57.000
Minus the variable costs, 500 rubles per unit of variable costs,

11:57.000 --> 12:02.000
multiplied by 750 units equals 375,000.

12:02.000 --> 12:05.000
Hence, we get the marginal profit.

12:05.000 --> 12:09.000
In units, this is 400 rubles per unit.

12:09.000 --> 12:14.000
Thus, we either multiply 400 by 750,

12:14.000 --> 12:20.000
or subtract 675 minus 375.

12:20.000 --> 12:26.000
In both cases, we get 300,000 rubles of marginal profit.

12:26.000 --> 12:31.000
Minus the constant costs.

12:31.000 --> 12:38.000
That is, 300,000 minus 200,000 equals 100,000 rubles.

12:38.000 --> 12:43.000
100,000 rubles of net profit that we get.

12:43.000 --> 12:45.000
That is, we see the whole dynamics.

12:45.000 --> 12:49.000
We see the loss area up to 500,000.

12:49.000 --> 12:54.000
We see the point of occupancy, the point of non-profitability,

12:54.000 --> 12:59.000
when we covered all the constant costs, but nothing more.

12:59.000 --> 13:04.000
And we see the area in which we get the profit.

13:04.000 --> 13:09.000
Everything we produce above 500 units,

13:09.000 --> 13:13.000
we get the net profit.

13:13.000 --> 13:20.000
Now we use this concept to calculate the point of non-profitability

13:20.000 --> 13:27.000
in units of the metal product for the same society with limited responsibility.

13:28.000 --> 13:32.000
Thus, the point of non-profitability, BE,

13:32.000 --> 13:38.000
in units, is equal to FC, that is, constant costs,

13:38.000 --> 13:43.000
divided by CM, that is, contribution margin,

13:43.000 --> 13:47.000
or marginal profit per unit.

13:49.000 --> 13:55.000
200,000 divided by 900 minus 500

13:55.000 --> 14:01.000
equals 200,000 divided by 400 equals 500 units.

14:01.000 --> 14:08.000
Please note that we calculated the same number of units produced and sold

14:08.000 --> 14:11.000
in order to cover all the constant costs,

14:11.000 --> 14:15.000
but we did it in a slightly different way.

14:15.000 --> 14:21.000
In previous examples, we divided the constant costs

14:21.000 --> 14:28.000
by the difference between the volume of sales and the variable costs.

14:28.000 --> 14:34.000
Now we operate directly with the value of the marginal profit.

14:34.000 --> 14:40.000
That is, we divide the constant costs by the marginal profit per unit.

14:40.000 --> 14:46.000
And we get 500 units, which is the point of occupancy.

14:46.000 --> 14:52.000
Now we calculate the point of non-profitability in rubles by multiplying

14:52.000 --> 14:57.000
the value of the point of occupancy in units, that is, BE,

14:57.000 --> 15:02.000
in units, by the price of the sale, that is, SP,

15:02.000 --> 15:05.000
selling price per unit.

15:05.000 --> 15:10.000
BE, that is, the point of occupancy in rubles,

15:11.000 --> 15:15.000
is equal to SP, that is, the price of the sale,

15:15.000 --> 15:19.000
selling price, SP, multiplied by BE,

15:19.000 --> 15:24.000
that is, the break-even point, or the point of occupancy in units.

15:24.000 --> 15:31.000
This is equal to 900 rubles multiplied by 500 units

15:31.000 --> 15:36.000
equals 450,000 rubles.

15:37.000 --> 15:41.000
Now we calculate the point of non-profitability in rubles

15:41.000 --> 15:45.000
by using the coefficient of marginal profit.

15:45.000 --> 15:54.000
So we divide the constant costs by the coefficient of marginal profit,

15:54.000 --> 15:58.000
or contribution margin rate.

15:58.000 --> 16:01.000
R is the word rate.

16:02.000 --> 16:12.000
So we divide 200,000 by 0.444 equals 45,045.

16:14.000 --> 16:18.000
The contribution margin rate, from here we see,

16:18.000 --> 16:23.000
is equal to the contribution margin, CM,

16:23.000 --> 16:28.000
divided by SP, that is, the selling price.

16:29.000 --> 16:34.000
The contribution margin, divided by the selling price,

16:34.000 --> 16:38.000
is equal to 400 divided by 900.

16:38.000 --> 16:42.000
400 rubles, the contribution margin,

16:42.000 --> 16:47.000
is divided by the sale of one unit,

16:47.000 --> 16:49.000
by the price of the sale of one unit,

16:49.000 --> 16:55.000
that is, it is equal to 444 after the comma, or 4 ninths.

16:58.000 --> 17:04.000
And if we divide the constant costs by this value,

17:04.000 --> 17:11.000
we will get 45,045 rubles,

17:11.000 --> 17:14.000
the point of occupancy in rubles.

17:16.000 --> 17:23.000
Now we will move on to calculate the assortment of products

17:23.000 --> 17:27.000
and use the aforementioned concepts,

17:27.000 --> 17:32.000
that is, the contribution margin or the marginal profit,

17:32.000 --> 17:39.000
in order to determine the distribution of the assortment of products.

17:39.000 --> 17:46.000
That is, without the concept of contribution margin or marginal profit,

17:46.000 --> 17:51.000
it would be very difficult for us to calculate the assortment of products

17:51.000 --> 17:55.000
and determine the point of occupancy and costs for the assortment of products.

17:55.000 --> 18:00.000
Let's first define what the assortment of products is.

18:00.000 --> 18:04.000
This is the proportion of sales of units of each product

18:04.000 --> 18:08.000
relative to the total sales of units of this organization.

18:08.000 --> 18:11.000
We modify the previous task,

18:11.000 --> 18:14.000
associated with the Metal Product Society.

18:14.000 --> 18:18.000
Now it sells two types of plant stands.

18:19.000 --> 18:25.000
This is a field stand for plants and a table stand for plants.

18:25.000 --> 18:28.000
The company sells 500 stands,

18:28.000 --> 18:33.000
300 of them are field stands, and 200 are table models.

18:33.000 --> 18:36.000
So, let's define the assortment of products.

18:36.000 --> 18:39.000
For each of the three sold field stands,

18:39.000 --> 18:42.000
two table models are sold.

18:42.000 --> 18:46.000
Thus, the assortment of products is 3 to 2,

18:46.000 --> 18:49.000
or, out of 500 sold stands,

18:49.000 --> 18:55.000
60%, that is, 300 divided by 500, are field models,

18:55.000 --> 19:01.000
and 40%, 200 divided by 500, are table models.

19:03.000 --> 19:07.000
We will do this work in several steps.

19:07.000 --> 19:09.000
So, step 1.

19:09.000 --> 19:13.000
Calculate the average marginal profit.

19:14.000 --> 19:18.000
Multiply the marginal profit for each product

19:18.000 --> 19:22.000
by its percentage share in the assortment of products.

19:22.000 --> 19:27.000
This is the table that does this calculation.

19:27.000 --> 19:29.000
What do we see here?

19:29.000 --> 19:33.000
We see calculations for two types of stands,

19:33.000 --> 19:37.000
a field stand and a table stand.

19:37.000 --> 19:41.000
The columns are called as follows.

19:41.000 --> 19:45.000
The retail price in rubles, SP,

19:45.000 --> 19:49.000
the variable costs, VC,

19:49.000 --> 19:53.000
the marginal profit in rubles, CM,

19:53.000 --> 20:01.000
the percentage share and the average marginal profit, CM.

20:01.000 --> 20:06.000
For a field stand, 900 is the retail price,

20:06.000 --> 20:08.000
minus 500.

20:08.000 --> 20:14.000
The variable costs are equal to the marginal profit of 400.

20:14.000 --> 20:20.000
But we have established that since we have 3 to 2,

20:20.000 --> 20:25.000
that is, we have 60% of the field stands

20:25.000 --> 20:28.000
in the total volume of the assortments.

20:28.000 --> 20:32.000
That is, we must multiply the marginal profit

20:32.000 --> 20:37.000
by 60%, which is the percentage share.

20:37.000 --> 20:40.000
That is, we must multiply the marginal profit

20:40.000 --> 20:44.000
by 60%.

20:44.000 --> 20:48.000
We get 240 rubles,

20:48.000 --> 20:52.000
which is the average marginal profit

20:52.000 --> 20:56.000
that we got for the field stand.

20:56.000 --> 21:01.000
Let's repeat the same calculations for the table stand.

21:01.000 --> 21:07.000
Now we see that the retail price of the table stand is 400.

21:07.000 --> 21:11.000
The variable costs are 200 per unit.

21:11.000 --> 21:15.000
The marginal profit, the marginal contribution

21:15.000 --> 21:19.000
will be equal to 400 minus 200.

21:19.000 --> 21:21.000
This is 200.

21:21.000 --> 21:23.000
Multiply by the percentage share.

21:23.000 --> 21:28.000
We remember that we have 3 field stands

21:28.000 --> 21:32.000
that correspond to 2 table stands.

21:32.000 --> 21:36.000
We produce 3 field stands for 2 table stands.

21:36.000 --> 21:40.000
Thus, we multiply 200 by 40%

21:40.000 --> 21:44.000
and we get the average marginal profit

21:44.000 --> 21:46.000
equal to 80.

21:46.000 --> 21:50.000
Next, we add two quantities.

21:50.000 --> 21:58.000
240 plus 80 equals 320.

22:00.000 --> 22:02.000
Now let's move on to the next step.

22:02.000 --> 22:04.000
Step 2.

22:04.000 --> 22:09.000
Calculate the average point of non-profitability.

22:09.000 --> 22:14.000
To do this, we need to divide the total

22:14.000 --> 22:19.000
constant costs into the average marginal profit.

22:19.000 --> 22:23.000
The average point of non-profitability

22:23.000 --> 22:27.000
equals the total constant costs

22:27.000 --> 22:33.000
divided into the average marginal profit.

22:33.000 --> 22:42.000
That is, 320,000 divided by 320.

22:43.000 --> 22:51.000
320,000 divided by 320 equals 1,000.

22:54.000 --> 22:56.000
Step 3.

22:56.000 --> 23:01.000
Calculate the point of non-profitability for each product.

23:01.000 --> 23:07.000
To do this, we need to multiply the average point of non-profitability

23:07.000 --> 23:12.000
by the percentage share for each product.

23:14.000 --> 23:20.000
So, we produce 1,000 of them.

23:22.000 --> 23:27.000
We multiply 1,000 by the percentage share

23:27.000 --> 23:33.000
equal to 60% for the field stand

23:33.000 --> 23:36.000
and we get 600.

23:37.000 --> 23:45.000
Then we multiply 1,000 by the percentage share

23:45.000 --> 23:50.000
for the table stand and we get 400.

23:51.000 --> 23:57.000
Now let's check whether we calculated the percentage share correctly.

23:58.000 --> 24:03.000
To check, we will determine the marginal profit for each product

24:03.000 --> 24:06.000
and subtract the total constant costs.

24:06.000 --> 24:09.000
The marginal profit is equal to

24:09.000 --> 24:16.000
the field stand 600 times 400.

24:16.000 --> 24:23.000
600 times 400 equals 240,000 rubles.

24:23.000 --> 24:33.000
The field stand 400 times 200 equals 80,000 rubles.

24:34.000 --> 24:40.000
The total marginal profit is equal to 320,000 rubles.

24:40.000 --> 24:47.000
Minus the constant costs, we get the profit equal to zero.

24:47.000 --> 24:48.000
Why?

24:48.000 --> 24:54.000
Because our goal was to determine the amount

24:54.000 --> 25:01.000
that we should produce and sell in order to reach the point of non-profitability.

25:01.000 --> 25:11.000
This means that the amount produced above 600 field and 400 table stands

25:11.000 --> 25:16.000
will be a net profit.

25:32.000 --> 25:41.000
Now that we have determined the amount and the quantity of products we should produce,

25:41.000 --> 25:48.000
we will think about how to set prices for these units.

25:48.000 --> 25:53.000
The price is very important in order to sell the product.

25:53.000 --> 25:57.000
We should remember the laws of economics,

25:57.000 --> 26:02.000
that there is a ratio of prices and demand.

26:02.000 --> 26:06.000
We know that the higher the price for a product,

26:06.000 --> 26:11.000
the lower the demand under equal conditions.

26:11.000 --> 26:13.000
And vice versa.

26:13.000 --> 26:20.000
The lower the price, the higher the demand under equal conditions.

26:20.000 --> 26:27.000
In this case, increasing the price will lead to a decrease in the amount of the product

26:27.000 --> 26:31.000
while maintaining the level of non-profitability.

26:31.000 --> 26:34.000
In this particular case,

26:34.000 --> 26:37.000
when conducting this marketing study,

26:37.000 --> 26:44.000
the price increase effect is set to 100 rubles for the company's operating profit.

26:44.000 --> 26:48.000
Since the competitors sell the same product at a lower price,

26:48.000 --> 26:55.000
the amount of the product will decrease by 15% if the price increases by 100 rubles.

26:55.000 --> 26:59.000
So, we decided to increase the price by 100 rubles

26:59.000 --> 27:05.000
and we see that the amount of the product will decrease by 15%.

27:05.000 --> 27:14.000
Now we should consider what will happen to our equations if we change the price ratio.

27:15.000 --> 27:21.000
We should determine how this decision will affect the operating profit.

27:21.000 --> 27:27.000
We see the table in which we make this calculation.

