36:28.000 --> 36:33.000
The cost of the system

36:39.000 --> 36:48.000
Now let's move on to the concept of standard costs and draw up the system of standard costs.

36:49.000 --> 36:57.000
Here we will try to give examples of three elements of the cost of a product.

36:58.000 --> 37:06.000
That is, we go from simple division of costs into constant variables to the elements of the cost of a product.

37:06.000 --> 37:15.000
Next, we will calculate the cost of a product unit and show its application using the example of the standard cost system.

37:15.000 --> 37:18.000
The cost of a product has three elements.

37:18.000 --> 37:29.000
These are direct costs of materials, direct costs of labor and production overhead costs, which are also known as indirect costs.

37:29.000 --> 37:32.000
What are direct material costs?

37:33.000 --> 37:46.000
Direct material costs are the costs of materials used in the production of a product, which can be conveniently and economically traced to certain units of the product.

37:46.000 --> 37:58.000
Examples. Iron ore used in the production of steel, sheet metal used in the creation of cars, sugar used in the production of sweets.

37:59.000 --> 38:02.000
All these are direct material costs.

38:02.000 --> 38:09.000
The more steel we produce, the more iron ore we require.

38:10.000 --> 38:13.000
The same is true for cars.

38:13.000 --> 38:16.000
We require more sheet metal.

38:16.000 --> 38:23.000
We can also attribute these direct costs to each unit of the product.

38:23.000 --> 38:33.000
For example, each new candy requires a certain amount of sugar that is put in this candy.

38:35.000 --> 38:47.000
Direct labor costs are the costs of labor, with which a product should be made and which can be conveniently and economically traced to certain units of the product.

38:48.000 --> 38:49.000
An example.

38:49.000 --> 38:53.000
The salary of the operators of the machines and workers of the pipeline.

38:53.000 --> 39:09.000
That is, every worker who makes a product spends labor, and the costs of his labor can be traced to each specific unit of this product.

39:11.000 --> 39:14.000
Next, we will talk about production overhead costs.

39:14.000 --> 39:25.000
Production overhead costs are related to production costs, which cannot be conveniently and economically traced to certain units of the product.

39:25.000 --> 39:32.000
They are also called factory overhead costs or indirect production costs.

39:33.000 --> 39:41.000
They include indirect material costs, nails, rivets, lubricants and small tools.

39:42.000 --> 39:53.000
Indirect labor costs, labor for the maintenance of the machine and the inspection, design of projects, and the observation and processing of materials.

39:54.000 --> 39:58.000
There are also other indirect production overhead costs.

39:59.000 --> 40:12.000
These are construction material and technical support, taxes, insurance, amortization of the plant and equipment, rent, utility payments, and much more.

40:13.000 --> 40:27.000
Production overhead costs are indirect costs distributed by the cost of the product, by the traditional or functional cost analysis method.

40:28.000 --> 40:35.000
This method is also known as ABC, Activity Based Costing.

40:36.000 --> 40:40.000
But in Russia it is called functional cost analysis.

40:40.000 --> 40:45.000
So, how is the cost of a product calculated?

40:46.000 --> 41:00.000
The cost of a product is calculated by the cost of production of one unit of the product, including direct material costs, direct labor costs, and production overhead costs.

41:01.000 --> 41:06.000
These costs are accumulated as the product batch is produced.

41:06.000 --> 41:10.000
They are calculated in one of two ways when the batch is finished.

41:11.000 --> 41:18.000
They are calculated by dividing the total accumulated costs into the total number of units produced.

41:19.000 --> 41:28.000
They are calculated by determining the cost per unit for each element of the product and by summing up the costs per unit.

41:28.000 --> 41:39.000
The information on the cost per unit helps managers to set prices for products and calculate the total margin and net income.

41:40.000 --> 41:44.000
The total margin is also called the total profit.

41:45.000 --> 41:50.000
The cost per unit of a product can be calculated using the following methods.

41:50.000 --> 42:05.000
The cost per unit is calculated by the actual costs, the cost per unit is calculated by the actual direct and indirect costs, and the cost per unit is calculated by the standard costs.

42:06.000 --> 42:12.000
So, the method of calculating the cost per unit is based on the standard costs.

42:13.000 --> 42:26.000
The cost per unit is calculated by the standard costs of direct materials, direct labor, and production overhead costs.

42:27.000 --> 42:31.000
What is the difference between standard and standard?

42:32.000 --> 42:48.000
In Russian, the word is used to describe standard costs, but in English, the word standard is translated as standard, which can be described as standard.

42:49.000 --> 42:59.000
This method is useful when it is desirable to have information on the cost of a product before the accounting period begins.

43:00.000 --> 43:09.000
The following goals are to control the costs for operational activities and price education for the offered product for the consumer.

43:09.000 --> 43:17.000
The illustration of the method of calculating the cost per unit is based on the standard costs.

43:18.000 --> 43:29.000
So, we have a chocolate company that places an order for the production of 2,000 chocolate bars for a new customer.

43:30.000 --> 43:35.000
The accounting manager of the company estimated the following costs.

43:36.000 --> 43:55.000
Direct materials, 2 rubles per piece, direct labor costs, 1.5 rubles per piece, production overhead costs, which are spent using the reference estimate of 60% of direct labor costs.

43:55.000 --> 44:00.000
Let's calculate the cost per unit of the product for the order.

44:01.000 --> 44:13.000
The reference estimate of production overhead costs is 90 kopecks per piece or 0.9 rubles per piece.

44:13.000 --> 44:34.000
This is equal to 1.5 times the direct labor costs, which are 60%, because the condition says that 60% of direct labor costs.

44:35.000 --> 44:44.000
Direct labor costs are called DL, which means direct labor.

44:46.000 --> 44:53.000
Direct materials are called DM, that is, direct materials.

44:53.000 --> 45:11.000
The reference estimate of production overhead costs is 1.5 times the direct labor costs, which are 60%.

45:12.000 --> 45:20.000
1.5 times 60% is equal to 90 kopecks or 0.9 rubles.

45:20.000 --> 45:43.000
Now we can add all three types of labor costs, 2, 1.5, 0.9, and we see that the cost of one chocolate bar will be 4.4 rubles, that is, 4 rubles and 40 kopecks.

45:59.000 --> 46:06.000
Now we move on to the last issue of our discussion today.

46:07.000 --> 46:11.000
These are the theoretical foundations of the Direct Cost system.

46:12.000 --> 46:19.000
Direct costs are costs that can be conveniently and economically traced to the object of value.

46:20.000 --> 46:34.000
For example, the cost of the flight to the air fleet, direct costs, crew salary, time spent and hourly salary are shown in the table of work time and payment notice.

46:35.000 --> 46:36.000
Fuel costs.

46:37.000 --> 46:48.000
Thus, we can say how many direct costs will be used for one flight to the air fleet.

46:48.000 --> 46:56.000
We have already discussed this issue today, so here is a repetition of the material already discussed.

46:57.000 --> 47:06.000
But we use this method to evaluate the work of the profit center.

47:07.000 --> 47:09.000
What is a profit center?

47:10.000 --> 47:30.000
In order to enhance and increase the efficiency of the work of production units in business that do not work directly on the market, three types of centers of responsibility are used, one of which is the profit center.

47:31.000 --> 47:44.000
There is a cost center, there is a profit center, and there is also an investment center.

47:45.000 --> 47:51.000
What is the difference between these three centers of responsibility?

47:52.000 --> 48:02.000
The cost center is based on the accumulation of costs for this center.

48:03.000 --> 48:17.000
It records how much is allowed for the work of this center, for the work of a business limited by the framework of this center.

48:17.000 --> 48:25.000
This can be a business segment, a division, a separate production plant.

48:26.000 --> 48:39.000
Since it does not work directly on the sale of finished products and on the trade, we cannot say how much it costs in market prices.

48:39.000 --> 48:42.000
We can only control its costs.

48:43.000 --> 48:48.000
Thus, this center has only a budget, but it does not have a profit.

48:49.000 --> 48:58.000
Unlike the profit center, since it really works on the final consumer, it sells its products.

48:58.000 --> 49:02.000
Therefore, it is called a profit center.

49:03.000 --> 49:10.000
Its work is evaluated by comparing the results of the actual profit report with the planned profit report.

49:11.000 --> 49:20.000
Accordingly, we can apply the direct costs method to evaluate the work of this profit center.

49:21.000 --> 49:25.000
This is the direct costs method.

49:26.000 --> 49:37.000
This is a method of preparing a report on the work of a profit center that classifies the managed costs of the manager as direct or permanent.

49:38.000 --> 49:45.000
Instead of the traditional profit report, a profit report is prepared using the direct costs method.

49:46.000 --> 49:55.000
It is also called a cost calculation with a full distribution of costs or absorption calculation.

49:56.000 --> 50:03.000
The word absorption comes from the word absorb, that is, to absorb, to distribute.

50:04.000 --> 50:08.000
This method is used for external accounting purposes.

50:09.000 --> 50:15.000
It is similar to the marginal profit report, since it pursues the same goals.

50:16.000 --> 50:26.000
It is useful because it focuses on changing the cost and contribution, or marginal profit, of the profit center to the operating income.

50:26.000 --> 50:34.000
That is, if we previously considered the marginal profit formula applicable to one unit of the product,

50:35.000 --> 50:42.000
now we can apply the same approach to the entire production or trading unit.

50:43.000 --> 50:49.000
Direct costing is used to evaluate the work of a profit center.

50:49.000 --> 51:02.000
The variable cost of the sold goods and the variable components of commercial and administrative expenses are subtracted from the sale to obtain the marginal profit for the profit center.

51:03.000 --> 51:11.000
All the managed permanent costs are subtracted from the gross margin to determine the operating income.

51:12.000 --> 51:20.000
It includes the permanent production costs and the permanent commercial costs.

51:21.000 --> 51:38.000
When preparing a profit report in the traditional format, all production costs are related to the cost of the sold goods.

51:38.000 --> 51:54.000
I want to remind you that the cost of the sold goods, which you probably studied in the main course of accounting, is the amount paid for the goods that were sold.

51:55.000 --> 52:00.000
The cost of the sold goods is recognized at the time of the sale of the goods.

52:00.000 --> 52:14.000
That is, we buy goods, store them, and after they are sold, the cost of the sold goods is part of the cost of the sale.

52:15.000 --> 52:20.000
The cost of the sold goods is subtracted from the sale to obtain the gross margin.

52:21.000 --> 52:28.000
Then, the variable permanent costs of the sale are subtracted from the gross margin to determine the operating income.

52:28.000 --> 52:38.000
This is the structure of the profit report in the traditional format, which is known from the accounting course.

52:39.000 --> 52:51.000
Now we will compare the profit report in the Direct Cost system and the profit report in the traditional format.

52:52.000 --> 52:55.000
What is the similarity and the difference?

52:55.000 --> 53:10.000
The profit report in the traditional format is the sale minus the cost of the sold goods equals the gross margin minus the period costs.

53:10.000 --> 53:25.000
What are the period costs? These are commercial costs, administrative costs, operating expenses that were allowed in the specified period.

53:26.000 --> 53:32.000
The difference between the gross margin and the period costs is the profit of the center.

53:33.000 --> 53:38.000
Now let's see what the Direct Cost report looks like.

53:39.000 --> 53:42.000
Sales minus all variable costs.

53:43.000 --> 53:52.000
Please note that the cost of the sold goods is not included in the cost of the goods.

53:53.000 --> 54:06.000
It does not include the variable costs that were in the commercial and administrative costs, which is a necessary part of any profit report.

54:07.000 --> 54:10.000
We subtract all variable costs here.

54:11.000 --> 54:17.000
And we get not a gross margin, but a marginal profit.

54:17.000 --> 54:25.000
This is a marginal profit, a marginal contribution to the coverage of the constant costs.

54:26.000 --> 54:45.000
And then we take not the period costs, but all the constant costs, that is, the investments that were made and which do not depend on how the volume of the produced or sold goods changes.

54:45.000 --> 54:50.000
And so we get the profit of the profit center.

54:51.000 --> 54:58.000
We see that the traditional profit report and the Direct Cost report differ.

54:59.000 --> 55:04.000
How can this be agreed upon with the requirement for accounting?

55:04.000 --> 55:05.000
It is very simple.

55:06.000 --> 55:10.000
The traditional profit report is a part of the financial accounting.

55:11.000 --> 55:14.000
It can be used as a tax accounting.

55:15.000 --> 55:22.000
It can be used to disclose information for financial markets.

55:23.000 --> 55:30.000
At the same time, the profit report on the Direct Cost system is a part of the administrative accounting.

55:30.000 --> 55:33.000
It is a part of the administrative accounting.

55:34.000 --> 55:39.000
And its purpose is to serve for the analysis and adoption of administrative decisions.

55:40.000 --> 55:48.000
The Direct Cost profit report groups the costs according to whether they are variable or constant.

55:49.000 --> 56:04.000
The traditional profit report groups the costs according to whether they are the costs of the goods sold or produced or the period costs.

56:05.000 --> 56:11.000
Again, we see that there are different purposes of the report.

56:12.000 --> 56:21.000
Now let's analyze what the accounting and administrative accounting can be used for.

56:22.000 --> 56:30.000
We know that the administrative accounting pursues two main goals.

56:30.000 --> 56:41.000
The main goal is to manage, that is, to make decisions aimed at the future and to control, which is aimed at the past.

56:42.000 --> 56:52.000
The traditional profit report, being a financial report, being an accounting report, can also serve as the purpose of the administrative accounting,

56:53.000 --> 57:00.000
where it controls how the costs were made in the past period.

57:00.000 --> 57:11.000
How effectively the goods were bought, at the right price, corresponding to the level of sales,

57:12.000 --> 57:18.000
what were the commercial administrative costs, that is, what were the costs of the period.

57:18.000 --> 57:29.000
Thus, the business can be controlled based on the traditional profit report, which is what it exists for.

57:30.000 --> 57:42.000
However, the Direct Cost profit report is designed and specifically designed to make administrative decisions.

57:42.000 --> 57:50.000
This report serves as the basis for making decisions for the future operation of the company.

57:51.000 --> 58:08.000
Now we will see how the difference between the Direct Cost profit report and the traditional profit report works,

58:08.000 --> 58:13.000
and how the profit report works with the same data for the same company.

